 The smallest positive integer \( x \) which leaves remainders of 3, 4, and 5 when divided by 4, 5, and 6 respectively, can be found by solving the system of congruences: \[
\begin{cases} 
x \equiv 3 \pmod{4} \\
x \equiv 4 \pmod{5} \\
x \equiv 5 \pmod{6} 
\end{cases}
\]

We can write \( x \) in the form \( x = 4k + 3 \), where \( k \) is an integer. Substituting \( x = 4k + 3 \) into the second congruence, we get \( 4k + 3 \equiv 4 \pmod{5} \), which simplifies to \( 4k \equiv 1 \pmod{5} \). Multiplying both sides by the modular inverse of 4 modulo 5 (which is 4 since \( 4 \cdot 4 \equiv 16 \equiv 1 \pmod{5} \)), we get \( k \equiv 4 \pmod{5} \), so \( k = 5m + 4 \) for some integer \( m \). Substituting \( k = 5m + 4 \) back into \( x = 4k + 3 \), we get \( x = 4(5m + 4) + 3 = 20m + 19 \). Now, we substitute \( x = 20m + 19 \) into the third congruence: \( 20m + 19 \equiv 5 \pmod{6} \), which simplifies to \( 20m + 19 \equiv 2m + 1 \equiv 5 \pmod{6} \), thus \( 2m \equiv 4 \pmod{6} \), or \( m \equiv 2 \pmod{3} \), so \( m = 3n + 2 \) for some integer \( n \). Substituting \( m = 3n + 2 \) back into \( x = 20m + 19 \), we get \( x = 20(3n + 2) + 19 = 60n + 40 + 19 = 60n + 59 \). The smallest positive integer \( x \) occurs when \( n = 0 \), so \( x = 59 \). </think> <answer> 59 </answer>

 The problem states that $x$ leaves a remainder of 3 when divided by 4, a remainder of 4 when divided by 5, and a remainder of 5 when divided by 6. This can be written in terms of congruences as follows: \[
\begin{cases}
x \equiv 3 \pmod{4} \\
x \equiv 4 \pmod{5} \\
x \equiv 5 \pmod{6}
\end{cases}
\]
By rewriting the congruences in a more useful form, we get: \[
\begin{cases}
x + 1 \equiv 0 \pmod{4} \\
x + 1 \equiv 0 \pmod{5} \\
x + 1 \equiv 0 \pmod{6}
\end{cases}
\]
This means that $x + 1$ is a common multiple of 4, 5, and 6. The smallest such common multiple is the least common multiple (LCM) of 4, 5, and 6. The LCM of 4, 5, and 6 is 60. Therefore, \[
x + 1 = 60k \quad \text{for some integer } k.
\] The smallest positive value for $x$ occurs when $k = 1$, so \[
x + 1 = 60 \quad \Rightarrow \quad x = 59
\]
